results.description:
Chapter 3 in my bird behavior series.
Photo 1: Turkey Vulture In Front Of My House
I very slowly walked out of my house and half way across my yard where I stood by my pecan tree trunk very still.  The turkey vulture was very large and much prettier than I expected with some lovely colors in its feathers.  It stood on the squirrel claiming its meal.  I had never seen one so close.
Photo 2:  Turkey Vulture Starts To Feed
I stood very still & after about a minute, the vulture started to eat.  Apparently it had already started on a meaty part of the squirrel before I came out of the house.  There was no sign of the crow that had found the meal first.
Photo 3:  Turkey Vulture Goes Deep
Enlarging the opening to get to the fresh meat.  Hard as it may be to watch, it is performing a great service to the neighborhood.  Clean up on my street.
Photo 4:  This Meat Is A Bit Stringy
Apparently squirrel meat can be a bit stringy.  I still could not believe the size of the vulture and that it was so close.  I had never seen one eating their meal before. 
Photo 5:  Enlarging The Opening
Doing the same thing the crow had been doing in the eye socket.  Inserted the beak deep then opened it slowly to enlarge the opening.  
Photo 6:  
Feeding Close Up
The bald featherless head makes more sense when you have observed a turkey vulture feeding.  I am curious why the white warts in front of the eyes.  
Photo 7:  Nice Bite Of Meat
I was still amazed I was able to be so close to the turkey vulture while it fed.  It was totally ignoring me & enjoying its meal.  I am also surprised there were no other vultures around.  
Photo 8:  Turkey Vulture Spots Me
I absently mindedly scratched my nose and that is when the vulture noticed me.  It stopped eating and froze for a few moments. 
Photo 9:  Turning Its Back On Me
Once it had noticed me, the vulture stopped eating and turned its back on me.  It looked one more time to see if I was still there, then it started walking away.
Photo 10:  Walking Away From Me
It was actually funny as the vulture stomped slowly away from me like it was mad about having its meal interrupted.  
Chapter 1 can be found here:  https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/9068504
Chapter 2 can be found here:  https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/9081559
